This paper focuses on the challenge of verifying the correctness of molecular implementations of abstract chemical reaction networks, which involves managing the complexity of designed molecular systems. This problem relates to the verification of Petri nets, which falls under the category of computer engineering (cs.CE). The paper also presents a new theory of pathway decomposition that provides a formal basis for comparing chemical reaction network implementations, which involves handling concurrent and asynchronous processes, and potentially infinite state spaces. This suggests that the paper may also fall under the categories of data structures (cs.DS), logic in computer science (cs.LO), systems and control (cs.SY), and programming languages (cs.PL).
